english:
  title: The Spirit of Earth
  author: Lee Kyu-bo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Liu Mengde once said, "Heaven, being purely yang, cannot be questioned directly—one must inquire of the Great Equilibrium." Thus, she who is paired with the Celestial Honored One is the Empress, the Earth Spirit. Since the Empress cannot be questioned directly, I posed my inquiry to the Spirit of the Five Soils under her dominion: "You are but a single, stolid thing suspended between heaven and earth. Yet you do not merely bury lifeless matter—gold and jade, stone and iron, tiles and rubble, the detritus of treasure. You also bury people. The sagely like Confucius, the virtuous like Yan Hui, the pure like Bo Yi, the filial like Zeng Zi, the steadfast like Guo Ziyi, the fearless like Li Su, the literary giants like Han Yu and Liu Zongyuan, the poetic masters like Li Bai and Du Fu—with their vast wisdom and boundless capacity, their brilliant essence and transcendent bearing that rivals the grandeur of heaven itself—how could you bear to bury them? Yet you also contain the obsequious like Jiang Chong, the vile like Liang Ji, the deceivers who deluded their lords, the thieves who stole kingdoms like An Lushan and Shi Siming—their treachery reeking, their poison unbearable—and you have consented to bury them as well?"

    The Spirit of Earth replied: "You are greatly mistaken. All things return their roots to soil—such is the natural way. How could I be selective in what I bury? I was appointed by Heaven and serve as the deity of Earth. All things, great and small, good and evil, I bury equally. Yet hear this: concerning people, there is a difference. Some I bury in body but not in spirit, while others I bury in spirit as well as bone. Did you know this?

    Those who are sagely, virtuous, incorruptible, filial, loyal, or fierce—those whose talents shine brilliantly—their essential spirits return to Heaven, or else are reborn among humanity as devoted children and pure ministers, or as exemplary heroes and worthy persons. Their bones I may bury, but their spirits and souls I cannot contain.

    But those who are obsequious, thieving, deceitful, cunning, and wicked—their spirits I can bind and their souls I can imprison. I cast them into my depths, cover them with my thickness, and even then it feels insufficient. With great stones from my treasury I pin them down, with surging waters from within me I seal them away. Thus I do not merely bury their bones, but I truly bury their spirits and souls as well."

    I said, "How right you are." And so I have recorded the Spirit's reply.
  footnotes:
    - The 'Great Equilibrium' (大鈞) refers to the cosmic force that maintains balance between heaven and earth.
    - The Five Soils (五土) represent the earthly realm governed by the Earth Spirit, counterpart to the Celestial Honored One.
    - The virtuous and wicked figures cited are drawn from Chinese history and legend, exemplifying moral excellence and depravity.
    - The dialogue uses the metaphor of burial to explore the distinction between physical death and the fate of one's spiritual essence and moral legacy.
